SCRI needs the equivalent of StS strikes/defends in the form of basic attackers, basic saboteurs and basic influencers. It would make some sense then to have: 

 - 2 basic attackers
 - 2 basic saboteurs
 - 2 basic influencers

(6 card package)

...and then on top of that, 2 uniques for the Aegis and 4 uniques for the Agents (2 each). This would split the deck completely evenly, which means specialization is tilted by the unique pool while the deck remains capable of doing all of the basic stuff. 

The JACL should also have a Syntac (magic) school, and the Agents should each have a unique Lex (mage) (2 of the same). When a Lex is played, a modal should pop-up allowing the player to drag both the magic school associated with the JACL and the magic school associated with the Lex into either their hand or the board, or just click outside of the modal to dismiss it. 

I think part of deck identity will revolve around whether or not the basic package stays, because the Agents / JACL support those cards and have ways of allowing them to scale / remain relevant, or is replaced and upgraded because the Agents / JACL have means of converting them... but with soome sort of flexibility trade-off or lack of player control over how the basics are replaced. So, player-directed deck thinning should be very limited, like in StS / PoC, but some archetypes might naturally still thin themselves and/or upgrade basics in ways the player can't control but are (arguuably) still beneficial. Also, I don't not want skipping cards to be an option. IMHO, this is the cleanest way to confront the issue of 'Skip Adding Card' simply being the best option. Because if skipping cards is allowed... it is almost certainly going to just be the best option, which in turn discourages players from actually engaging with the card pool and making decisions based on what they are going to draft rather than decisions based on what has already been drafted. 

